data_poll <- read_excel("~/Documents/School/Spring 2025/Math 250/Mid term 2/pizza_poll.xlsx")
data_ratings <- read_excel("~/Documents/School/Spring 2025/Math 250/Mid term 2/pizza_ratings.xlsx")

Question 1

data_poll <- data_poll %>% 
  mutate(score = case_when(
    answer == "Excellent" ~ 5,
    answer == "Good" ~ 4,
    answer == "Average" ~ 3,
    answer == "Fair" ~ 2,
    answer == "Never Again" ~ 1,
    TRUE ~ NA_real_))
    
Q_1_Table <- data_poll %>% 
  filter(!is.na(score)) %>%
  group_by(place) %>%
  summarize(
    tot_p = sum(score * votes, na.rm = TRUE),
    tot_resp = sum(votes, na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_rat = round(tot_p / tot_resp, 2)
  ) %>%
  filter(tot_resp >= 15) %>%
  arrange(desc(avg_rat)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10) %>%
  gt()

Question 2

Hypotheses

  • Null: \(H_0: ExpensiveRating\mu = CheapRating\mu\)

  • Alternative: \(H_a: ExpensiveRating\mu \ne CheapRating\mu\)

Graph

Q2_Graph <- data_ratings %>%
mutate(price_group = case_when(
  price_level %in% c(0, 1) ~ "Cheap (0â1)",
  price_level %in% c(2, 3) ~ "Expensive (2â3)",
  TRUE ~ NA_character_  
))
ggplot(Q2_Graph, 
       aes(x = price_group, 
          y = rating, 
          fill = price_group)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "summary", 
           fun = "mean") + 
  labs(title = "Average Critic Rating by Price Level",
       x = "Pizza Price Group",
       y = "Average Rating") +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2")

Test

cheap <- data_ratings %>% 
  filter(price_level %in% 
           c(0, 1)) %>% 
  pull(rating)
expensive <- data_ratings %>% 
  filter(price_level %in% c(2, 3)) %>% 
  pull(rating)

t.test(expensive, cheap, alternative = "greater")

    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  expensive and cheap
t = 4.3183, df = 432.84, p-value = 9.755e-06
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 0.4389531       Inf
sample estimates:
mean of x mean of y 
 6.991171  6.281217

Conclusion

The p-value is smaller than our significance level p = 9.755*10^-6 meaning that the null hypothesis is rejected and the alternative hypothesis is accepted. In other words, Higher pizza prices likely lead to higher average ratings for said pizza.

Question 3

poll_scores <- data_poll %>%
  filter(!is.na(score)) %>%
  group_by(place) %>%
  summarize(poll_rating = sum(score * votes, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(votes, na.rm = TRUE)) 

# Then join with critic ratings
merged_data <- data_ratings %>%
  inner_join(poll_scores, by = c("name" = "place")) %>%
  rename(critics_rating = rating)

# Plot
ggplot(merged_data, aes(x = critics_rating, y = poll_rating)) +
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "red", linetype = "dotted") + 
  labs(
    title = "Relationship Between Critics' Ratings and Poll Ratings",
    x = "Critics' Rating",
    y = "Poll Rating"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()

There appears to be a weak positive relationship between the 2 variables. In other words poll voters and pizza critics are in some agreement on pizza quality.

Lets confirm using a linear model

lm_model <- lm(poll_rating ~ critics_rating, data = merged_data)
summary(lm_model)

Question 4

data_spot <- read_csv("~/Documents/School/Spring 2025/Math 250/Mid term 2/spotify_sample.csv")

Hypotheses

Null: \(H_0:\) The mean energy level is the same across all genres

Alternative: \(H_a:\) At least one genre has a different mean energy level

Graph

ggplot(data_spot, 
       aes(x = energy, 
           y = genre,
           fill = genre)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  labs(title = "Energy Levels Across Music Genres",
       x = "Genre",
       y = "Energy Level") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Test

anova_model <- aov(energy ~ genre, 
                   data = data_spot)
summary(anova_model)
             Df Sum Sq Mean Sq F value   Pr(>F)    
genre         5 0.6834 0.13668   5.902 6.88e-05 ***
Residuals   114 2.6399 0.02316                     
---
Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

Since the p-value is so small this supports that we reject the null hypothesis and and accept the alternative hypothesis, lets do a Tukey Post hoc test to see:

Conclusion

There is strong statistical evidence that the average energy level differs by genre as the p-value of p < 6.88*10^-5 suggests that we reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis. In other words, this suggests that genre and energy level are not independent.

Question 5

Hypotheses

Null: \(H_0:\)There is no correlation between energy and tempo

Alternative: \(H_a:\) There is a correlation between energy and tempo

Graph

ggplot(data_spot, 
       aes(x = tempo, 
           y = energy)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, alpha = 0.7) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", 
              se = FALSE, 
              color = "red", 
              linetype = "dotted") +
  labs(title = "Relationship Between Tempo and Energy of Songs",
       x = "Tempo (BPM)",
       y = "Energy Level") +
  theme_minimal()

Test

lm_model <- lm(energy ~ tempo, data = data_spot)
summary(lm_model)

Call:
lm(formula = energy ~ tempo, data = data_spot)

Residuals:
     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

F-statistic: 0.633 on 1 and 118 DF,  p-value: 0.4278

Conclusion

The p-value is quite large(p = 0.4278) thus we fail to reject the null hypothesis. In other words, tempo and energy appear to be independent in this sample.

Question 7

top_motives <- data_scoob %>%
  count(motive, 
        sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_head(n = 3) %>%
  pull(motive)

top_terrains <- data_scoob %>%
  count(setting_terrain, 
        sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_head(n = 2) %>%
  pull(setting_terrain)

scooby_sm <- data_scoob %>%
  filter(format == "TV Series",
         motive %in% top_motives,
         setting_terrain %in% top_terrains) %>%
  select(title,motive, setting_terrain)

Question 8

Hypotheses

Null: \(H_0:\) There is no association between motive and setting terrain (they are independent).

Alternative: \(H_a:\) There is an association between motive and setting terrain (they are dependent).

Graph

ggplot(scooby_sm, 
       aes(x = motive, 
           fill = setting_terrain)) +
  geom_bar(position = "fill") + 
  labs(title = "Proportion of Motive by Setting Terrain",
       x = "Motive",
       y = "Proportion",
       fill = "Setting Terrain") +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Dark2") +
  theme_minimal()

Test

table_sm <- table(scooby_sm$motive, scooby_sm$setting_terrain)

chisq_test <- chisq.test(table_sm)

chisq_test

    Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction

data:  table_sm
X-squared = 0.040102, df = 1, p-value = 0.8413

Conclusion

The p-value = 0.8413 is much greater than the significance level, Therefore, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. In other words, the motive of the crime in the show and setting terrain appear to be independent in this case.
